Who Cares about Morality

Mariola Paruzel-Czachura, Cillian McHugh

06 November, 2022

Overview

Testing for Country Effects

Internalization

Initial testing revealed that for Internalization, allowing intercepts to vary with Country significantly improved the predictive power of the model \(\chi\)2(1) = 5564, p < .001.

Predictors (Individual Level Only)

Internalization

model1 <- lmerTest::lmer(moral_identity_internal ~
                    sex3
                  * age
                  + (1|country)
                , data = x
                , contrasts = list(sex3 = contr.sum, valence = contr.sum )
            )

Predictors (Cultural Variables Included)

Internalization

model1 <- lmerTest::lmer(moral_identity_internal ~
                    sex3
                    * (age
                    + Power.Distance
                    + Individualism
                    + Masculinity
                    + Uncertainty.Avoidance
                    + Long.Term.Orientation
                    + Indulgence
                    + CTL_C
                    + CTL_DS
                    + CTL_DG)
                  + (1|country)
                , data = x
                , contrasts = list(sex3 = contr.sum, valence = contr.sum )
            )

(Regular Regression)

We also ran a regression without allowing slopes to vary by country. Results are below:

fit <- lm(moral_identity_internal ~
                    sex3
                    + age
                    + Power.Distance
                    + Individualism
                    + Masculinity
                    + Uncertainty.Avoidance
                    + Long.Term.Orientation
                    + Indulgence
                    + CTL_C
                    + CTL_DS
                    + CTL_DG
                , data = x
            )
